04098nam a22006135i 9780292797512DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212004txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927975127 a10.7560/7016322doi  a(DE-B1597)587845  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aTT293b.W45 2004eb 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a621.9/322221 aWhittaker, John C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerican Flintknappers :bStone Age Art in the Age of Computers /cJohn C. Whittaker. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2004  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction: Coming to the Knap-in -- t2 Making Stone Tools: The World’s Oldest Craft -- t3 From Fakes and Experiments to Knap-ins: The Roots of Modern Flintknapping -- t4 The Knap-in: People and Organization -- t5 Knappers at the Knap-in -- t6 Status and Stones -- t7 Art, Craft, or Reproduction: Knapper Esthetics -- t8 Can’t Never Have Too Much Flint: The Lore of Stone -- t9 Modern Stone Age Economics -- t10 Knappers, Collectors, Archaeologists: Ethics and Conflicts -- t11 Silicon and Society -- tAppendix A Knapper Mail Survey Questionnaire -- tAppendix B Fall 1966 Fort Osage Knap-in Registration -- tAppendix C New York Knap-in Contest Rules, 1994 -- tAppendix D New York Knap-in Contest Rules, 1996 -- tBibliography -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMaking arrowheads, blades, and other stone tools was once a survival skill and is still a craft practiced by thousands of flintknappers around the world. In the United States, knappers gather at regional "knap-ins" to socialize, exchange ideas and material, buy and sell both equipment and knapped art, and make stone tools in the company of others. In between these gatherings, the knapping community stays connected through newsletters and the Internet. In this book, avid knapper and professional anthropologist John Whittaker offers an insider's view of the knapping community. He explores why stone tools attract modern people and what making them means to those who pursue this art. He describes how new members are incorporated into the knapping community, how novices learn the techniques of knapping and find their roles within the group, how the community is structured, and how ethics, rules, and beliefs about knapping are developed and transmitted. He also explains how the practice of knapping relates to professional archaeology, the trade in modern replicas of stone tools, and the forgery of artifacts. Whittaker's book thus documents a fascinating subculture of American life and introduces the wider public to an ancient and still rewarding craft.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aFlintknapping. 0aStone implements. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292797512423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292797512/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK